WHAT IS THIS KINGDOM
The domain that quantifies the difference between how a human observer
perceives light, color, and detail and how a camera sensor captures them.
It defines the biological limits of the Human Visual System (HVS), the
laws of perceptual adaptation, the origins of logarithmic encoding, and
the design logic behind every OETF, EOTF, tone mapper, and color
appearance model used in modern imaging.

WHY IT EXISTS
A camera records linear photon counts; a human sees a scene via a
complex, nonlinear, and adaptive biological processor. Ignoring this
gap leads to flat tonal gradation, incorrect highlight roll-off, color
inconsistency, and viewer discomfort. This kingdom provides the
perceptual mandate for every transform in the GIOP pipeline, ensuring
that the final image is not just numerically accurate but visually
faithful to the original scene.

HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Seven sub-domains: HVS Architecture, Luminance Adaptation,
Dynamic Range Gap, Spectral Sensitivity and Metamerism, Perceptual
Encoding (OETF/EOTF design), Tone Mapping and Color Appearance, and
Practical Consequences for the Imaging Pipeline. Each section provides
the defining biological or psychophysical equations alongside the
corresponding camera-side equations, exposing the exact mathematical
distance that GIOP transforms must bridge.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
In-camera log curve design (S-Log3, LogC4, Log3G10, F-Log2), HDR
transfer function specification (PQ, HLG), display EOTF calibration,
tone mapping operator (TMO) design for format conversion, ACES Output
Transform design, color appearance modeling for cross-media reproduction,
and quality assurance for cinematic looks.

WHO USES IT
Camera engineers designing log curves, color scientists defining
working spaces, pipeline TDs implementing tone mappers, and colorists
who need to understand why a specific grade feels right or wrong.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Eliminates the "flat HDR" syndrome by anchoring log curves to the eye's
compressive response. Fixes metamerism mismatches between camera RGB and
human LMS cones. Provides the perceptual rationale for tone mapping,
ensuring that HDR content on an SDR display retains artistic intent.
Prevents viewer fatigue caused by incorrect luminance encoding. Converts
imaging from a purely engineering exercise to a biologically respectful
visual art.

1. HUMAN VISUAL SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
The retina contains two classes of photoreceptors.
Rods (approximately 120 million): operate below 0.005 cd/m^2 (scotopic),
  peak sensitivity at 507 nm (V'(lambda)), no color discrimination.
Cones (approximately 6 million): three types, L, M, S, with peak
  sensitivities at approximately 560 nm, 530 nm, and 420 nm respectively.
  Active above 5 cd/m^2 (photopic), provide trichromatic color vision.

Mesopic range (0.005 to 5 cd/m^2): both rods and cones active,
luminosity function shifts gradually from V'(lambda) to V(lambda).
CIE 191:2010 provides mesopic photometry.

Receptor distribution is highly non-uniform. Cones are densely packed
in the fovea (central approximately 2 degree field), while rods dominate
the periphery. This is why the 2 degree CIE 1931 standard observer uses
foveal cone fundamentals; the 10 degree CIE 1964 supplementary observer
incorporates some rod contribution.

2. LUMINANCE ADAPTATION AND THE WEBER-FECHNER LAW
The visual system adapts to ambient luminance over an enormous range
(10^-6 to 10^8 cd/m^2). This adaptation involves pupil dilation,
photoreceptor gain control, and neural adaptation.

Weber's Law: within a given adaptation state, the just-noticeable
difference (JND) in luminance Delta L is proportional to the background
luminance L:
  Delta L / L = k (k approximately 0.02 for a wide range of luminance levels)
This implies that visual sensitivity to luminance differences is
logarithmic.

Fechner's formulation: perceived brightness B = c * ln(L/L0).
In modern terms, the photoreceptor response follows a compressive
Naka-Rushton equation:
  R / R_max = L^n / (L^n + sigma^n)
where n is approximately 0.7 to 1.0 and sigma is the semi-saturation
constant. The response compresses highlights and expands shadows,
creating the biological basis for log gamma curves.

3. DYNAMIC RANGE GAP: EYE vs CAMERA
Instantaneous dynamic range (DR) of the HVS (single adaptation state)
is approximately 10 to 14 stops (1000:1 to 16000:1). Total adaptive DR
exceeds 20 stops. Modern CMOS sensors achieve 14 to 17 stops of linear DR.

The eye achieves high DR via local adaptation: each region of the retina
adapts independently, effectively applying a spatially varying gain map.
A camera sensor captures a globally uniform linear response, requiring
a global tone curve to compress the scene DR into the display's limited
range.

Key difference: the eye's effective OETF is local and temporal; the
camera's OETF must be globally applied to every pixel. This is the
fundamental reason why single-global-log-curve cameras still fail to
perfectly mimic human vision in extreme contrast scenes.

4. SPECTRAL SENSITIVITY AND METAMERISM
The LMS cone fundamentals define the spectral sensitivity of the human
observer. The CIE 1931 2 degree color matching functions x_bar, y_bar,
z_bar are linear transformations of these fundamentals.

A camera's RGB spectral sensitivities (including IR cut and color filter
array) do not exactly match any linear combination of the LMS
fundamentals. This leads to observer metamerism: two spectrally
different stimuli that match for the human eye may produce different
camera RGB values, and vice versa.

Camera color correction matrices (e.g., from sensor RGB to XYZ or ACES)
are designed to minimize metamerism error for a given illuminant and
set of training colors, but residual error always exists. Spectral
imaging (31 bands, 400 to 700 nm) eliminates this error and is the
reference truth for GIOP.

5. PERCEPTUAL ENCODING: OETF AND EOTF DESIGN
All encoding transfer functions are designed around the HVS contrast
sensitivity function (CSF) or the Weber-Fechner law.

SDR OETF (e.g., BT.709, sRGB): approximate gamma 2.2 or 2.4,
mimicking the inverse of the perceptual response over a luminance
range of about 100:1. The linear section near black reduces sensor
noise amplification.

HDR OETF (HLG): Hybrid Log-Gamma (ITU-R BT.2100) uses a square-root
portion near black and a logarithmic portion for highlights:
  E' = sqrt(3*E)/2   for 0 <= E <= 1/12
  E' = a * ln(12*E - b) + c   for E > 1/12
This provides backward compatibility with SDR displays while encoding
extended dynamic range.

HDR EOTF (PQ): ST 2084 Perceptual Quantizer is derived from Barten's
CSF model and defines the JND step as exactly one code level over the
range 0 to 10 000 cd/m^2. The formula:
  V = ((c1 + c2 * L^m1) / (1 + c3 * L^m1))^m2
with constants defined in the Standard (m1=0.1593, m2=78.84, c1=0.8359,
c2=18.85, c3=18.69). This ensures that the bit depth (10 or 12 bits) is
fully utilized without visible banding.

All camera log curves (S-Log3, LogC4, Log3G10, F-Log2) approximate a
perceptually uniform encoding by applying a logarithmic function to
linear scene light. Their mathematical forms are documented in GIOP
Bodies. They share the same design principle: mid-grey (18%) maps to
approximately the middle of the 10-bit code value range, leaving equal
JND steps for shadows and highlights.

6. TONE MAPPING AND COLOR APPEARANCE MODELS
Tone Mapping Operators (TMOs) convert scene-referred linear luminance
to display-referred luminance, mimicking human adaptation.

Simple global TMOs: Reinhard (L_d = L / (1+L)), exponential, filmic
(ACES RRT). Their purpose is to compress highlights while preserving
local contrast.

Color Appearance Models go beyond luminance and model chromatic
adaptation, surround effects, and brightness/colorfulness attributes.
CIECAM02 and CAM16 are the most widely accepted. They accept XYZ
tristimulus values, adapting field luminance (L_A), and surround
parameters, and output perceptual correlates: lightness J, chroma C,
hue h, brightness Q, etc.

GIOP mandates the use of CAM16 for any cross-display or cross-ambient
color matching. The forward model from XYZ to CAM16 JCh and the inverse
are defined in CIE 248:2022.

The ACES 2.0 Gamut Compression algorithm operates in a perceptual
space derived from CAM16, compressing out-of-gamut colors toward the
achromatic axis while preserving hue with less than 2 degree shift.

7. PRACTICAL CONSEQUENCES FOR THE GIOP PIPELINE
- IDT design must handle the camera's linear capture, not mimic the eye.
  Perceptualization happens only at the output stage via ODT.
- Log grading spaces (ACEScct, LogC, etc.) are preferred by colorists
  because they approximate the eye's JND distribution: equal code value
  steps correspond to roughly equal perceived differences.
- The ODT must include not just the EOTF but also a rendering intent
  that accounts for display peak luminance and surround (dark, dim, or
  average). This is where CAM16-based mapping is invoked.
- For virtual production, the LED wall's luminance must be calibrated
  so that the camera seeing the wall perceives the same relative
  luminances as the human eye seeing the real scene. This requires a
  camera-and-eye co-model, provided by Kingdom 01 and deployed via
  GIOP's volumetric rendering tools.

